2","1286":"1286","1362":"1362","1 August 1332":"1 August 1332","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","Dupplin, Perthshire, Scotland":"Dupplin, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Forbes, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Forbes, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Forbes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Forbes in Tullynessle, Aberdeenshire, so named from Gaelic <i>forba</i> ‘field, district’ + the locative suffix <i>-ais</i>. The placename is pronounced in two syllables, with the stress on the second, and the surname until recently reflected this. Today, however, it is generally a monosyllable.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Firbhisigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearbhisigh</i>’, a personal name composed of elements meaning ‘man’ + ‘prosperity’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) in Connacht was famous for its traditional historians, compilers of the Book of Lecan."],"variants":[{"name":"Fawbush","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which ispronounced as two syllables in Aberdeenshire. Compare   Forbush  ."]},{"name":"Forbus","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , reflecting thetraditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Forbush","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Forbes  , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Altered form of German <b>Vorbusch</b>, a topographic name for someone living on the edge of a wood, from <i>vor</i> ‘in front of’ + North German <i>Busch</i> ‘wood, bush’."]},{"name":"Fobbs","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Furbush","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which is traditionally pronounced as two syllables. Compare   Furbish  ."]},{"name":"Forbis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Fobes","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Forbess","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Forbes was born in 1286, in Forbes, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, his father, Alexander Forbes, was 30 and his mother, Mrs Alexander John De Forbes, was 28. He married Mrs Alexander DeForbes in 1310, in Forbes, Aberdeenshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 1 August 1332